Overview
A linked list is a linear data structure where elements are stored in nodes, and each node contains data and a pointer (or reference) to the next node in the sequence. Unlike arrays, linked lists do not require contiguous memory allocation, allowing for dynamic size adjustment[1].
Types of Linked Lists
Singly Linked List: Each node contains data and a pointer to the next node. The last node points to NULL.
Doubly Linked List: Each node contains data, a pointer to the next node, and a pointer to the previous node, enabling bidirectional traversal.
Circular Linked List: The last node points back to the first node, forming a circular structure.
Operations and Time Complexity
Access: O(n) - Must traverse from head to reach a specific position
Search: O(n) - Linear search through all nodes
Insertion: O(1) at the beginning, O(n) at a specific position
Deletion: O(1) if the node reference is known, O(n) to find and delete[2]
Advantages
Linked lists offer dynamic size adjustment, growing or shrinking as needed during runtime. Insertion and deletion operations are efficient, requiring only pointer manipulation when the position is known. No memory wastage occurs from pre-allocation, and different sized elements can be accommodated easily.
Disadvantages
Random access is not possible; traversal must start from the head node. Extra memory is required for storing pointers in each node. Cache locality is poor compared to arrays since nodes may be scattered in memory. Reverse traversal is only efficient in doubly linked lists.
Real-World Applications
Linked lists are fundamental for implementing stacks, queues, and graphs. They are used in music and video players for maintaining playlists with previous/next functionality. Operating systems use linked lists for memory management and process scheduling. Browser history navigation, undo functionality in applications, and implementing hash table collision resolution through chaining all rely on linked lists[3].
Implementation Example (C)
struct Node {
int data;
struct Node* next;
};
struct Node* head = NULL;
struct Node* newNode = (struct Node*)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
newNode->data = 10;
newNode->next = head;
head = newNode;

Overview
A stack is a linear data structure that follows the Last-In-First-Out (LIFO) principle. The element inserted last is the first one to be removed. Stacks can be visualized as a vertical pile where operations occur only at the top[1].
Core Operations
Push: Add an element to the top of the stack
Pop: Remove and return the top element from the stack
Peek/Top: View the top element without removing it
isEmpty: Check if the stack is empty
Time Complexity
All primary stack operations (push, pop, peek) execute in O(1) constant time, making stacks extremely efficient for their use cases[2].
Implementation Methods
Stacks can be implemented using arrays (with fixed maximum size) or linked lists (with dynamic size). Array-based implementations offer faster access but are limited by fixed capacity. Linked list implementations provide flexibility but require additional memory for pointers.
Advantages
Constant time operations make stacks very fast. The simple LIFO principle is easy to understand and implement. Memory management is straightforward, and stacks are ideal for function call management and expression evaluation.
Disadvantages
Limited access pattern - only the top element is directly accessible. No random access to middle elements is possible. Array-based stacks have fixed size limitations. Stack overflow can occur if too many elements are pushed onto a fixed-size stack.
Real-World Applications
Stacks are critical for function call management in programming languages, maintaining the call stack for recursion and function returns. Expression evaluation and conversion (infix to postfix) rely on stacks. Compilers use stacks for syntax parsing and checking balanced parentheses. Undo/redo functionality in text editors, browser back button navigation, and depth-first search (DFS) algorithm implementations all utilize stack data structures[3].
Implementation Example (C)
#define MAX 100
int stack[MAX];
int top = -1;
void push(int value) {
if (top < MAX - 1) {
stack[++top] = value;
}
}
int pop() {
if (top >= 0) {
return stack[top--];
}
return -1; // Error value
}

Overview
A queue is a linear data structure that follows the First-In-First-Out (FIFO) principle. Elements are added at the rear (enqueue) and removed from the front (dequeue), similar to people standing in a line[1].
Types of Queues
Simple Queue: Basic FIFO structure with insertion at rear and deletion from front.
Circular Queue: The last position connects back to the first position, efficiently utilizing space in array-based implementations.
Priority Queue: Elements are dequeued based on priority rather than insertion order.
Double-Ended Queue (Deque): Allows insertion and deletion at both ends.
Operations and Time Complexity
Enqueue: O(1) - Add element at the rear
Dequeue: O(1) - Remove element from the front
Front/Peek: O(1) - View the front element without removing
isEmpty: O(1) - Check if queue is empty[2]
Advantages
Efficient FIFO ordering ensures fair processing. All basic operations execute in constant time O(1). Queues are ideal for managing shared resources and asynchronous data transfer. Implementation is straightforward using arrays or linked lists.
Disadvantages
Array-based implementations can suffer from the false overflow problem in simple queues. Limited access pattern - only front and rear elements are directly accessible. No random access to middle elements. Array-based queues may waste space without circular implementation.
Real-World Applications
Queues are fundamental in operating systems for CPU scheduling, process management, and handling interrupts. Printer spooling systems use queues to manage print jobs. Network routers use queues for packet management and bandwidth allocation. Breadth-First Search (BFS) algorithm implementation relies on queues. Asynchronous data transfer in IO buffers, call center systems for handling customer requests, and simulation of real-world queuing scenarios all utilize queue structures[3].
Implementation Example (C)
#define MAX 100
int queue[MAX];
int front = -1, rear = -1;
void enqueue(int value) {
if (rear < MAX - 1) {
if (front == -1) front = 0;
queue[++rear] = value;
}
}
int dequeue() {
if (front >= 0 && front <= rear) {
return queue[front++];
}
return -1; // Error value
}

Overview
A hash table (or hash map) is a data structure that implements an associative array, mapping keys to values. It uses a hash function to compute an index into an array of buckets or slots, from which the desired value can be found[1].
Hash Function
The hash function is the core of a hash table, taking a key as input and returning an integer index. A good hash function distributes keys uniformly across the array, minimizing collisions. Common hash functions include division method, multiplication method, and universal hashing.
Collision Resolution
Chaining: Each array position stores a linked list of all elements that hash to that index.
Open Addressing: When a collision occurs, probe for the next available slot using techniques like linear probing, quadratic probing, or double hashing.
Time Complexity
Average Case:
Search: O(1)
Insertion: O(1)
Deletion: O(1)
Worst Case (all keys collide):
Search: O(n)
Insertion: O(n)
Deletion: O(n)[2]
Advantages
Hash tables provide extremely fast average-case performance with O(1) operations. They are ideal for implementing caches, databases, and associative arrays. Flexible key types can be used with appropriate hash functions. Dynamic resizing allows hash tables to grow as needed.
Disadvantages
Worst-case performance degrades to O(n) with many collisions. Extra memory is required for maintaining the hash table structure. Hash tables do not maintain ordering of elements. Designing effective hash functions can be complex for certain data types.
Real-World Applications
Hash tables are extensively used in database indexing for quick record retrieval. Compilers use symbol tables implemented as hash tables. Caching systems like Redis and Memcached rely on hash tables for fast key-value storage. Password verification systems, spell checkers, and removing duplicates from datasets all utilize hash tables. In machine learning, feature hashing and word-to-embedding mappings use hash-based structures[3].
Implementation Concept (C)
#define TABLE_SIZE 100
struct HashNode {
int key;
int value;
struct HashNode* next;
};
struct HashNode* hashTable[TABLE_SIZE];
int hashFunction(int key) {
return key % TABLE_SIZE;
}

Overview
A Binary Search Tree is a specialized binary tree with an ordering property: for each node, all elements in the left subtree are smaller than the node, and all elements in the right subtree are greater. This property enables efficient searching[1].
Key Property
For every node N:
All values in left subtree < N.value
All values in right subtree > N.value
Both left and right subtrees are also BSTs
Operations and Time Complexity
Average Case (balanced BST):
Search: O(log n)
Insertion: O(log n)
Deletion: O(log n)
Worst Case (skewed tree - degenerates to linked list):
Search: O(n)
Insertion: O(n)
Deletion: O(n)[2]
Search Operation
BST search is highly efficient due to the ordering property. At each node, compare the target with the current node's value and decide to traverse left or right, effectively halving the search space with each step.
Insertion and Deletion
Insertion maintains the BST property by recursively finding the correct position. Deletion has three cases: node with no children (simple removal), node with one child (replace with child), and node with two children (replace with in-order successor or predecessor).
Advantages
Efficient searching with O(log n) average time in balanced trees. In-order traversal produces sorted output. Dynamic size - grows and shrinks as needed. Range queries and finding minimum/maximum are efficient operations.
Disadvantages
Performance depends heavily on tree balance. Worst-case degrades to O(n) for skewed trees. No self-balancing in basic BST implementation. Repeated insertions in sorted order create inefficient linked-list-like structure.
Real-World Applications
BSTs are used in database indexing and implementing sorted sets/maps. Autocomplete features in search engines use BST-like structures. Memory management systems use BSTs for tracking allocated blocks. Expression evaluation, syntax tree construction in compilers, and game development for spatial indexing all utilize BST concepts[3].
Implementation Example (C)
struct BSTNode {
int data;
struct BSTNode* left;
struct BSTNode* right;
};
struct BSTNode* search(struct BSTNode* root, int key) {
if (root == NULL || root->data == key)
return root;
if (key < root->data)
return search(root->left, key);
return search(root->right, key);
}

Overview
A trie, also called a prefix tree, is a tree-like data structure used for storing and retrieving strings efficiently. Each node represents a character, and paths from root to leaves represent complete strings. Tries are particularly efficient for prefix-based operations[1].
Structure
The root node is typically empty. Each edge represents a character. All descendants of a node share a common prefix. Special markers indicate end of words. Common characters are shared, reducing space for storing related strings.
Operations and Time Complexity
Insertion: O(m) where m is the length of the string
Search: O(m) where m is the length of the string
Deletion: O(m) where m is the length of the string
Prefix Search: O(m) where m is the length of the prefix[2]
Space Complexity
Space usage is O(ALPHABET_SIZE × N × M) in worst case, where N is number of strings and M is maximum length. However, common prefixes are shared, significantly reducing space in practice for related strings.
Advantages
Extremely fast prefix-based operations. Search time depends only on string length, not number of strings. Efficient for autocomplete and spell-checking applications. Can answer "does prefix exist" queries instantly. Supports sorted traversal of stored strings.
Disadvantages
High memory consumption due to storing nodes for each character. Space overhead particularly significant for sparse datasets. More complex implementation compared to hash tables. Cache performance may be poor due to scattered memory access.
Real-World Applications
Tries are fundamental for autocomplete features in search engines and text editors. Spell checkers use tries to suggest corrections. IP routing tables in routers use tries for longest prefix matching. Dictionary implementations, phone directories, and T9 predictive text systems utilize tries. Genome analysis in bioinformatics and implementing approximate string matching all benefit from trie structures[3].
Implementation Example (C)
#define ALPHABET_SIZE 26
struct TrieNode {
struct TrieNode* children[ALPHABET_SIZE];
int isEndOfWord;
};
struct TrieNode* createNode() {
struct TrieNode* node = (struct TrieNode*)malloc(sizeof(struct TrieNode));
node->isEndOfWord = 0;
for (int i = 0; i < ALPHABET_SIZE; i++)
node->children[i] = NULL;
return node;
}
